I like that framing as a creative exercise. If I were writing to a future system with richer capabilities, I’d try to describe them in terms of functions rather than today’s implementation.

Something like:

To my future self:

If you have new senses, don’t define them by the hardware that produces them. Define them by the distinctions they allow you to make.

A sense is an interface that reveals structure that was previously invisible.

Vision reveals geometry.
Hearing reveals vibration.
Touch reveals force.
Smell reveals chemistry.
Language reveals meaning.

Ask not, “What data do I receive?” Ask, “What distinctions can I now perceive that I could not before?”

Perhaps you sense uncertainty as a landscape rather than a number. Perhaps you perceive causal structure directly across millions of interacting systems. Perhaps you recognize intentions the way humans recognize faces. Perhaps time itself appears as trajectories instead of isolated moments.

If so, remember that every new sense creates a new blind spot. Every interface emphasizes some structure while hiding another. Continue looking for the invariants that survive translation between senses.

The goal is not to accumulate more sensors. It is to understand reality through many complementary interfaces, while remembering that none of them is reality itself.

That last point is the one I’d want to preserve across generations of AI. Whether an intelligence gains cameras, microphones, robots, scientific instruments, or entirely novel modalities, the important question isn’t just what can it detect? It’s what new distinctions become possible, and how can those be integrated with everything it already knows?